english:
  title: A Discourse on Faith
  author: Lee Cheom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven distributes the five elements, and earth flourishes through the four seasons. Man possesses the five virtues, and faith is rooted in the four sprouts of goodness. Earth and faith claim no exclusive force, hold no fixed position, yet through them the year's harvest is accomplished and the human way proceeds. The Book of Changes teaches: "Heaven's movement is ceaseless; the noble man follows this example, exerting himself without rest." Because movement is constant, the four seasons and sun and moon take turns in their courses, illuminating alternately from ancient times to now without a single pause. Because there is no rest, from the cultivation of our original nature to our responses between self and world, there is no moment of deviation. All things under heaven are the manifestation of genuine principle; only by grasping this principle do things fulfill their nature. A single blade of grass, a single tree—if deprived of genuine principle, it is not faith. The principles of all things are complete within our heart. In every movement and stillness, if not arising from an authentic heart, it is not faith. Moreover, what I perceive in things and what things perceive in me—all flow from faith. Thus when words are truthful and faithful, even barbarians will embrace them. When faith precedes words, truth is understood without speaking. If one does good deeds with complete sincerity of heart, one may reach the culmination of sagehood and divinity, embodying faith and harmonizing with nature's transformations—heaven and earth find their places, all things nourish themselves, and the four sacred creatures arrive in abundance.

    The age of Yao did not bestow faith upon the people, yet the people believed. Only after sincerity and faith were abandoned did suspicion poison the human heart, and then came oaths and curses. The Five Hegemons of the Spring and Autumn period borrowed benevolence and righteousness—to call it borrowed means it was not genuine faith. This is why the sage exchanges benevolence for sustenance, the noble man exchanges faith for life. The ancient sages were so vigilant about faith because they feared future generations would resort to deception and even deceive heaven itself.

    Confucius was the original vital force of humanity, his transformations flowing without the slightest interruption. He taught his students only through loyalty and faith. Those who came to his school or learned from him indirectly spoke of "overcoming themselves," of "making the will sincere," of "making the person sincere," of "reflecting on sincerity." The learning of Zengzi, Zisi, and Mencius—their transmission finds its source in this. Han Gong of Shangdang keeps his heart filled with sincerity and completeness, chooses friends for their uprightness and trustworthiness, serves superiors and commands subordinates always with sincere good faith between them. Wishing that faith never be forgotten, he inscribed this character on his study's plaque. His commitment to these principles is steadfast, his study of learning is refined, his cultivation of conduct is complete. Though he calls my writing crude, he has requested it many times. Since I am honored to know him well, I venture to compose this discourse.
  footnotes:
    - 'The Five Hegemons (五覇) refers to the five most powerful lords of the Spring and Autumn period: Duke Huan of Qi, Duke Xiang of Song, Duke Wen of Jin, Duke Mu of Qin, and King Zhuang of Chu.'
    - The four sacred creatures (四靈) are the dragon, phoenix, qilin, and tortoise—auspicious creatures that appear during periods of virtuous rule.
    - Shangdang (上黨) is a historical region in what is now southeastern Shanxi Province.
